{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.33,0.54,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9800"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5055"},{"type":"tags","id":"10075"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26413"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECholestyramine is a medication used to treat hypercholesterolaemia. It is an anion exchange resin that is not absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases bile acid synthesis without binding","Blocks intestinal cholesterol absorption","Binds bile acids in intestine preventing reabsorption","Enhances excretion of cholesterol in bile","Directly inhibits cholesterol synthesis in liver"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of cholestyramine is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinds bile acids in the intestine preventing reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E. This interrupts the enterohepatic circulation of bile acids, leading to increased conversion of cholesterol to bile acids in the liver to replace those lost in faeces. The net effect is a reduction in serum cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases bile acid synthesis without binding\u003C/strong\u003E is a secondary effect that occurs only after bile acids are bound and lost in the faeces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile cholestyramine may have a minor effect on cholesterol absorption, \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking intestinal cholesterol absorption\u003C/strong\u003E is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances excretion of cholesterol in bile\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as cholestyramine does not directly influence the biliary excretion of cholesterol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly inhibits cholesterol synthesis in liver\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect; cholestyramine has no direct effect on hepatic cholesterol synthesis, which is the mechanism of action of statins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs cholestyramine binds substances in the gut, it can interfere with the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) and many medications. Therefore, other medications should be taken at least four hours before or after cholestyramine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholestyramine is a bile acid sequestrant that binds bile acids in the intestine, preventing their reabsorption.","By interrupting enterohepatic circulation of bile acids, cholestyramine indirectly lowers cholesterol by increasing hepatic conversion of cholesterol to bile acids.","Cholestyramine can interfere with absorption of fat-soluble vitamins and many medications due to its binding properties."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T09:33:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T09:34:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9800"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","positi